# Supabase usage

This project uses `@supabase/ssr` (the consolidated replacement for the
deprecated `@supabase/auth-helpers-*` family). Always pick the correct
client for the context:

| Context                                    | Helper                                                              |
| ------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Client Component, hook, event handler      | `createClient` from `@/lib/supabase/client`                         |
| Server Component, Server Action, Route Handler | `await createClient()` from `@/lib/supabase/server`             |
| Trusted server work that bypasses RLS      | `createAdminClient()` from `@/lib/supabase/admin` (server-only)     |
| `src/proxy.ts` only                        | `updateSession(request)` from `@/lib/supabase/session`              |

Authorization rules:

- Use `supabase.auth.getClaims()` for any decision that gates routing or
  data access. It validates the JWT.
- `getSession()` reads cookies without verification — never use it to
  authorize.
- `getUser()` always hits the Supabase Auth server; reach for it when you
  need the current user record.

When adding new tables:

1. Enable Row Level Security (`alter table … enable row level security;`).
2. Add policies for `select`, `insert`, `update`, `delete` as appropriate.
3. Regenerate `src/lib/supabase/types.ts` so the typed clients pick up the
   new shape.
